CAD to GIS Semi - Automation¶

Created By: Data Team (PWA)
Date : 20th September, 2022

Updated : 25th Dec, 2022
Technical Report By: Kevin Gathogo

Introduction¶

Road data is usually huge,complex and aggregated from different specialised multi-disciplined contractors/sub-contractors. Irrespective of geometry, the submited data is varied in its characteristics, moreso the technical attributes . This is evident from the diverse scope, nature, location and materials involved in construction/Installation spanning from;

  • Signals and Signage
    • Trafic and Directional Sign
    • Traffic control and management (ITS)
    • Road Markings
  • Lighting
  • Layouts - Civil Work and Pavement (Road Lines and Carriageway)
  • Structures such as bridges and overpasses

Actually Qatar Traffic Control Manual is a 350 plus page document, heavy in content and details capturing roughly less than half of the PWA Roads database (Signages & Markings )

CAD to GIS conversion usually takes between 4-5 weeks depending on the complexity of the submitted road and the number of feature classes. Over time this has proven to be time-consuming.

Objective¶

These tools intend to:

  • Semi-Automate Conversion of CAD data to GIS data format. It maps and append each layer of Cad to its respective feature class.
  • Populate Primary/Common Attributes in all the feature classes.

NOTE:¶

- The scope does not involve topological editing of Road lines and Carriageway polygonization.
- It Overlaps with RFP1 - Automation.
- Its NOT embedded in any application, apart from Arcmap has a script.
- It enables a GIS Editor to focus on a soft QA/QC of the converted data, engage in minor edits, lessen the back and forth movement of from CAD to GIS during manual data extraction of individual features.
-Increases accuracy and completeness of the gathered data/information from CAD
-It saves time of the repetitive task such as appending CAD layers to different feature classes, Attribution etc.
-User friendly, with few parameters to input to run.
*-Works well when data is compiled in the given AutoCAD template catering for both Standard and Non-Standard.

Foristance if it takes a day to complete fully, a single asset such as traffic signs or streetlight pole (over 450 records in attribute table) or ducts, The tool greatly shorten that time, that in two to three day (Subject to nature of the project) you can have all assets in the gdb with Common Attributes saving on the numerous iterative geoprocessing operations.

CADToGeodatabase¶

We create three datasets

  • ASBUILT : - This is the ouput of our converted CAD to GIS in raw form (Point, Polyline, Polygon, Multipatch and Annotation)
  • ASBUILT_Point : - From the point feature class in ASBUILT Dataset, the Layers inside are converted to individual point features
  • ASBUILT_Polyline :- Similarly from polyline to individual layers of CAD
  • ASBUILT_Polygon:- From Polygon to individual layers

The reason for the above is to act as:

  • Backup to what will be appended later to various features classes in our schema
  • To be read and be appended based on some defined dictionary partially guided by PWA Standards

Extracting, Transforming and Loading¶

CAD to GIS Conversion can be looked at in the lens of an ETL process. Which is basically extracting data from one medium AutoCAD .dwg format and transforming it to a different data format (GIS format).
Then Loading of the transformed data into a gdb or SDE.

Appending Function¶

The below appending function takes layer name and check against pre-defined dictionary

In [21]:
def appendingfunction(x):
    #Create FieldMappings object to manage merge output fields
    fieldMappings = arcpy.FieldMappings()

    # Add the target table to the field mappings class to set the schema
    fieldMappings.addTable(x)

    # Add input fields for the feature remarks into featureRemarks field that matches the 
    # target dataset since each input dataset has a different field name for this info
    fldMap = arcpy.FieldMap()
    fldMap.addInputField(fc,"layer")
            
    # Set name of new output field "featureRemarks"
    featureRemarks = fldMap.outputField
    featureRemarks.name, featureRemarks.aliasName, featureRemarks.type = "FEATURE_REMARKS", "Remarks", "TEXT"
    fldMap.outputField = featureRemarks
            
    # Add output field to field mappings object
    fieldMappings.addFieldMap(fldMap)
            
    return(fieldMappings)

Primary / Common Attributes (Roads) - Based Ashghal GIS Standard¶

Primary / Common Attributes a:- Attributes that are repeated (or a common) in almost all feature classes in PWA Roads fgdb/EGIS. These attribute can be populated during conversion and appended on all the various CAD layers file instantly. Why the name Primary attributes? This is because they are populated from our in-house data without any external or secondary data source. Primarily from our , Namely;

  1. PROJECT_CODE
  2. PROJECT_STATUS
  3. PROJECT_TYPE
  4. SOURCE_DATA_INPUT_FORMAT
  5. DATA_INPUT_METHOD
  6. METADATA
  7. SOURCE_DEPT_SECTION_UNIT
  8. OWNER
  9. DATE_CREATED
  10. EDITED_BY
  11. LAST_UPDATED_DATE
  12. FEATURE_LEVEL
  13. PROJ_REF
  14. CONTRACT_NO
  15. FEATURE_STATUS

Secondary Attributes : - Attributes that we have to rely on data from secondary sources, e.g CGIS:

  1. RD_ANAME
  2. RD_ENAME
  3. STREET_NO
  4. ZONE_NO

Technical Attributes : - These are feature specific e,g Traffic sign code, streetlight pole height, Voltage etc.

def attributeUpdating(fc):
    
    start = time.process_time()
    
    field_names = [f.name for f in arcpy.ListFields(fc)]
    for key in general_attribute:
        if key in field_names:
            delimfield = arcpy.AddFieldDelimiters(fc, key)
            #print(key)
            value = general_attribute[key]
            #print(value)
            cursor = arcpy.da.UpdateCursor(fc, [key])
            for row in cursor:
                row[0] = value
                cursor.updateRow(row)
                del row
            del cursor
        #print(time.process_time() - start)
    return (fc)
